node.contents: Does that mean that it doesn't matter what JAR a class is in - it only matters what **package** it's in? Meaning, if class A is inside a JAR imported to the project from the outside, and class B was created inside the project - and both have no explicitly defined packages - it means that both of them are in the same package, the default one?

astNode.text: Does that mean that it doesn't matter what JAR a class is in - it only matters what **package** it's in? Meaning, if class A is inside a JAR imported to the project from the outside, and class B was created inside the project - and both have no explicitly defined packages - it means that both of them are in the same package, the default one?

node.contents: @Prog That's right. A `jar` is simply a solution for grouping `.class` files. In the end, when you provide a classpath to the JVM, it's all a bunch of `.class` files in corresponding packages. There's no differentiation between `.class` files in `jars` or anywhere else.

node.contents: So I don't need to write `import` because the class from the imported JAR is also in the default package?

astNode.text: So I don't need to write `import` because the class from the imported JAR is also in the default package?

node.contents: @Prog Right. The same thing would happen if your class was in package `org.example` and some other class was also in that package but it was in a separate jar on the classpath. This behavior doesn't only apply to the default package.

node.contents: The import statement is used to be able to refer to types and their members by their simple names. You don't need to import classes that are in the same package, unless they are nested members of other classes. This is true regardless of where the class comes from, for example, if it's in another .jar.

node.contents: The jre supplies a (rather comprehensive) standard library. This library contains classes you will most likely need to do anything serious with java. Take a look at http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/ - these classes (organized in packages) are available to you _without_ any further jars, just because you installed java,
